        "channelId": "UCJ0uqCI0Vqr2Rrt1HseGirg",

          "kind": "youtube#comment",

          "id": "Ugxp2wj5tf4o33SvMG94AaABAg",
          "snippet": {
            "channelId": "UCJ0uqCI0Vqr2Rrt1HseGirg",
            "videoId": "up1Wb2Q_WMk",
            "textDisplay": "I hate mass shootings as much as the next guy. But maniacs wielding scary-looking semi-automatic military-style rifles with high capacity magazines aren't, and have never been the biggest gun violence problem in America. It just seems that way because mass shootings by far garner the most media attention. Deaths from mass shootings, while tragic and worth trying to reduce, amount to a few hundred deaths a year; a small fraction of the total gun deaths each year \n\nThe greatest potential for saving lives otherwise lost each year due to gun violence is dramatically restricting how, when and where handguns may be carried, used or transported in America. Data from the 1993-2011 DOJ Study on Firearms Violence clearly proves this.  In 2011 there were 11,101 gun murders in America, 7360 of which (66 percent) were perpetrated with handguns. There were  another 18,000 gun suicides that year and over 450,000 non-fatal gun assaults, the vast majority committed using handguns. Folks, this is the low-hanging fruit on this issue. \n\nGun proponents might believe I am entirely anti-gun. That belief is incorrect. I have no issue with people owning sporting rifle, shotguns, muzzle loaders etc. But I am solidly anti-handgun, except for specific, limited uses. Certainly there are legitimate uses for owning or possessing firearms: legitimate collectors; protection from predators for those who work, hunt or recreate in nature; for target and competition shooting at gun ranges and for legitimate defense of family, home and property. Most people who own long guns and handguns for these purposes use and store these weapons responsibly. \n\nBut the simple fact is that there are a subset of Americans who fail to store their weapons safely, brandish their guns in public places to asset their carry rights, use guns as leverage to commit crimes or conceal handguns while out on the street or otherwise use guns illegally or irresponsibly. There are WAY more of these cretins in America  than any other country. Nearly 45% of all non-fatal gun assaults occur in the home, at a friend's or relative's home or near their home.  \n\nAmerica is perceived around the world as a gun-happy society, full of overly excitable people, where every citizens is constitutionally endowed with the right to own guns. That why most other nation's derisively refer to America as the 'excited states.' The combination of 350 millions guns owned by excitable, in some cases unstable, people  causes countless instances of people trying to solve interpersonal problems by shooting the other person. Canadians are more reserved, ad ha about a third as much gun violence as America per capita. British citizens are ever more reserved, and have even less gun violence. America's health care system lags behind most western democracies in recognizing and treating those with mental illness; \n\nSo how does America even begin to reduce handgun deaths and assaults while also fully respecting citizens' constitutional rights? Well, until NRA's grip on half of America's elected representatives' balls is broken, little will get done except for the ban on bump stocks. Clearly reform of corporate lobbying is badly needed. This goes hand-in-hand with the GOP's current unwillingness to entertain ANY gun reform measures. Some Democratic legislators aren't much better: a good example was Speaker Senator Harry Reed, whose Nevada constituency forced his no vote on the Obama gun reform bill in 2013. \n\nOther good steps might be to reduce magazine sizes for semi-automatic, military-style rifles like AR-15s and semi-auto handguns, to at least force mass shooters to reload more often. Increase the minimum training required for those who wish to own military-style semi-auto rifles, and compel them re-certify every few years. Eliminate legal handgun possession anywhere but out in the wilderness, at gun ranges, or while transporting them to/from those ranges or the wilderness. Amnesty and gun buy-back programs could take perhaps a couple hundred million guns out of US society over a generation or so. Less guns equals less gun violence, less gun crime. Universal background checks and mandatory waiting periods to buy guns could reduce gun deaths from crimes of passion. Enact substantially higher fines or even jail sentences for illegal stored guns, the latter for stolen guns used later to commit crimes.  \n\nRight now 92% of Americans polled favor universal background checks.
